Note:
Runtime mutex API — the public mutual-exclusion object for the Runa runtime
concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing object layer. The actual locking mechanism is the
completed cross-platform synchronization facade (sync_core), which itself
delegates to the per-architecture OS futex / ulock primitives. This module
does NOT re-implement locking; it wraps the sync_core handle in a runtime
RuntimeMutex object and adds the semantics a runtime contract requires that
the raw facade does not provide:

  - POISONING: a holder that detects an unrecoverable error in the data it is
    protecting marks the mutex poisoned. Subsequent acquirers still obtain the
    lock (mutual exclusion is still needed to inspect/repair the data) but are
    told MUTEX_ERR_POISONED so they can decide whether to recover or abort.
    This mirrors the poison model used by mature systems runtimes and is the
    standard way to surface "a previous critical section left this state
    inconsistent" without unwinding.
  - STANDARDIZED STATUS CODES: every entry point returns a MUTEX_* status so
    callers branch on a single, documented contract rather than the facade's
    raw 1/0 platform results.

RuntimeMutex layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0:  handle    — the sync_core mutex_ptr (the real lock)
    offset 8:  poisoned  — 0 healthy, 1 poisoned
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/sync_core.runa" as Sync
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory

Note: RuntimeMutex object layout
Constant RT_MUTEX_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE as Integer is 0
Constant RT_MUTEX_OFF_POISONED as Integer is 8

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime mutex API
Constant MUTEX_OK as Integer is 0
Constant MUTEX_ERR_NULL as Integer is -1
Constant MUTEX_ERR_POISONED as Integer is -2
Constant MUTEX_ERR_LOCK_FAILED as Integer is -3
Constant MUTEX_ERR_BUSY as Integer is -4

Process called "mutex_new" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a runtime mutex object. Mechanism (the OS lock) comes from sync_core;
    this layer adds the poison flag and a stable object identity callers hold.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 16-byte RuntimeMutex, create the underlying sync_core mutex,
    store its handle, and initialize the poison flag to healthy (0). On any
    allocation/creation failure, release whatever was acquired and return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One small allocation plus one sync_core mutex_create (which allocates its
    own 24-byte control block and an OS lock). Cold path: done once per mutex.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Failure returns 0 (NULL); callers MUST check before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let m be proc allocate from Memory with RT_MUTEX_SIZE
    If m is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let handle be proc mutex_create from Sync
    If handle is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with m
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE, handle
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_POISONED, 0
    Return m
End Process

Process called "mutex_acquire" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block until the lock is held, then report whether the protected state is
    trustworthy. The lock is acquired even when poisoned because the caller
    still needs exclusive access to inspect or repair the inconsistent data.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate the blocking acquire to sync_core mutex_lock. If that fails to
    report success, the lock is NOT held and we return MUTEX_ERR_LOCK_FAILED.
    Once held, return MUTEX_ERR_POISONED when the poison flag is set (the lock
    is still held and must be released), otherwise MUTEX_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core mutex_lock (fast user-space CAS on the uncontended path; OS
    futex wait only under contention) plus two field loads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns MUTEX_ERR_NULL without touching memory. When MUTEX_OK
    or MUTEX_ERR_POISONED is returned the lock IS held and the caller owns the
    obligation to release it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE
    Let r be proc mutex_lock from Sync with handle
    If r is not equal to 1:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_LOCK_FAILED
    End If

    Let poisoned be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_POISONED
    If poisoned is not equal to 0:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_POISONED
    End If
    Return MUTEX_OK
End Process

Process called "mutex_try_acquire" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking acquire for callers that must make progress rather than wait.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core mutex_try_lock. A 0 result means the lock is held by
    another owner (MUTEX_ERR_BUSY). On success, surface poison state exactly as
    mutex_acquire does so the held/poison contract is identical on both paths.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core mutex_try_lock (single CAS, never blocks) plus field loads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns MUTEX_ERR_NULL. The lock is held only when MUTEX_OK or
    MUTEX_ERR_POISONED is returned.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE
    Let r be proc mutex_try_lock from Sync with handle
    If r is not equal to 1:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_BUSY
    End If

    Let poisoned be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_POISONED
    If poisoned is not equal to 0:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_POISONED
    End If
    Return MUTEX_OK
End Process

Process called "mutex_release" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release a held lock. Must be called exactly once per successful acquire
    (including the MUTEX_ERR_POISONED acquire, which still holds the lock).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core mutex_unlock, which also clears its owner/count
    tracking. Return MUTEX_OK on success.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core mutex_unlock (user-space store on the uncontended path; a
    single futex wake when waiters are present).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns MUTEX_ERR_NULL. Releasing a lock not held by the caller
    is a logic error surfaced by the underlying facade.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with handle
    Return MUTEX_OK
End Process

Process called "mutex_is_held" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report whether the lock is currently held by any thread.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core mutex_is_locked (1 held, 0 free).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load inside the facade.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Advisory only; the state may change immediately after the call returns.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE
    Return proc mutex_is_locked from Sync with handle
End Process

Process called "mutex_owner" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return the thread id of the current owner, or 0 if unlocked.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core mutex_get_owner.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load inside the facade.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Advisory; for diagnostics and deadlock detection, not for ownership-based
    control flow.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE
    Return proc mutex_get_owner from Sync with handle
End Process

Process called "mutex_is_poisoned" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report whether a previous critical section flagged the protected data as
    inconsistent.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the poison flag (1 poisoned, 0 healthy).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_POISONED
End Process

Process called "mutex_poison" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mark the mutex poisoned. A holder that detects an unrecoverable failure in
    the protected state calls this before releasing so later acquirers are
    warned the data may be inconsistent.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the poison flag to 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Should be called while holding the lock so the flag is published before the
    next acquirer observes it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_POISONED, 1
    Return MUTEX_OK
End Process

Process called "mutex_clear_poison" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Clear the poison flag after a caller has repaired the protected state,
    returning the mutex to normal service.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the poison flag to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Should be called while holding the lock, after the inconsistent state has
    actually been repaired.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_POISONED, 0
    Return MUTEX_OK
End Process

Process called "mutex_destroy" takes m as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the OS lock and free the runtime object. Must not be called while
    the lock is held.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core mutex_destroy (which frees the facade control block
    and the OS lock), then deallocate the RuntimeMutex object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core mutex_destroy plus one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns MUTEX_ERR_NULL. Destroying a held lock is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If m is equal to 0:
        Return MUTEX_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with m, RT_MUTEX_OFF_HANDLE
    proc mutex_destroy from Sync with handle
    proc deallocate from Memory with m
    Return MUTEX_OK
End Process
